  "tags": [
    {
      "name": "Introduction-Overview",
      "x-displayName": "Overview",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  FarmENGAGE is an independent, brand agnostic platform that connects infield devices and operational workflows, to more efficiently execute crop production plans and collect the most robust dataset in the industry.<br /><br />In addition to delivering customer value around the Operational Workflow, the FarmENGAGE connects and enables compatibility with non-PTx Trimble platforms and applications that deliver additional value to the farmer. Enabling farmers to complete workflows that involve solutions from multiple technology providers is critical to our customers, especially in cases where 3rd party applications address unique regional farming practices, are preferred by local advisor networks, offer enhanced local technology support or address local regulatory policies.<br /><br />FarmENGAGE APIs are REST APIs that enable this value delivery.\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "Use Cases",
      "x-displayName": "Use Cases",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  The FarmENGAGE API allows users to accomplish a variety of tasks:<br />\n</div>\n\n- Align Client/Farm/Field, Boundaries, Guidance Lines, and Landmarks between&nbsp; 3rd party applications and FarmENGAGE Software/PTx Trimble Displays  \n- Send Prescriptions from 3rd party applications to FarmENGAGE Software/PTx Trimble Displays&nbsp;  \n- Send as-applied data from PTx Trimble Displays to 3rd party applications  \n- Many others…"
    },
    {
      "name": "Concepts",
      "x-displayName": "Concepts",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n</div>\n\n- Data flow within the FarmENGAGE Platform - Data from 3rd party applications is sent to FarmENGAGE and may then be automatically or manually sent to connected PTx Trimble Displays. Data from connected PTx Trimble Displays will be sent to FarmENGAGE and then may be sent to 3rd party applications.\n\n- In FarmENGAGE, Organizations are the basic structure that segregates user data. An organization typically represents the business entity that manages the resources (fields, equipment, personnel, materials) used in a farming operation. Each FarmENGAGE user account will have access to one or more organizations.\n\n- PTx Trimble Displays supported: \n\nGFX: 350, 750, 1060, 1260&nbsp;\n\nXCN: 750, 1050, 1060, 1260&nbsp;"
    },
    {
      "name": "Dependencies",
      "x-displayName": "Dependencies",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n</div>\n\n- To exchange data between a connected 3rd party application and a FarmENGAGE Organization the Organization must have a FarmENGAGE base license (eg. Data or Operations).&nbsp;\n\n- To connect to a FarmENGAGE Organization a PTx Trimble Display must have a FarmENGAGE display license (e.g. Display Connection)."
    },
    {
      "name": "Setup",
      "x-displayName": "Setup",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  Step-by-step instructions on how to get started with this API.\n</div>\n\n- Create Application  \n-- Request FarmENGAGE API credentials by filling out the form [here][1].  \n-- Grant Type Options - your application will be set up using one of the two options below. This decision depends on who will be accessing the API through your application.  \n1. Authorization Code Grant  \n**Operation** - allows confidential and public clients to exchange an authorization code for an access token via a trusted back channel.  \n**Use Case** - this configuration option utilizes user-level authorization. This is applicable when multiple users (i.e. your customers) log into the 3rd party application connected via API (your application) and every user should have access to the different organizations that they individually have access to through different FarmENGAGE logins.\n\n2. Client Credentials Grant  \n**Operation** - allows clients to obtain an access token outside of the context of a user with a secured environments.  \n**Use Case** - this configuration option utilizes application-level authorization. This is applicable when only a single entity (i.e. your business) logs into the 3rd party application connected via API (your application) and every user should have access to the same authorized organizations in FarmENGAGE.\n\n [1]: https://ptxtrimble.com/en/partners/developer-resources/request-software-integration-api"
    },
    {
      "name": "Connecting to FarmENGAGE APIs",
      "x-displayName": "Connecting to FarmENGAGE APIs",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n</div>\n\n- Authenticate your application to gain an access token. Note that your process will differ depending on whether your application is setup to use the Authorization Code Grant or Client Credentials Grant&nbsp; (see the instructions below).\n\n- Users authorize access to data in Organizations through an OAuth process you initiate (see the instructions below).\n\n- Connect to endpoints for accessing authorized organizations and exchanging data (see API documentation)."
    },
    {
      "name": "How-To-Overview",
      "x-displayName": "Overview",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  The \"How To\" section shows how to use the FarmENGAGE API to access or provide specific data as part of a distinct workflow. <br /><br />Additional information and other related endpoints can be found in the comprehensive list of API endpoints below.\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "Access-as-applied-data",
      "x-displayName": "Download As-applied Data",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  Download as-applied data using these steps.<br />1. GET the list of Equipment Activities<br />2. GET the list of Layers<br />3. GET the list of Samples\n</div>\n\n- **Step 1: <mark style=\"background-color:#00d084\" class=\"has-inline-color has-white-color\"> GET </mark> - <a href=\"/#operation/GetEquipmentActivities\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Get the list of Equipment Activities</a>**  \nThis will return the list of Equipment Activity tasks for an Organization in FarmENGAGE.  \n-- **API Call: {{BaseURL}}**/tasks/**{{OrgId}}**/equipmentactivities  \n-- **Path Variable:** Org ID  \n-- **Response:** A successful GET request will result in 200 OK status code along with the response body that includes a list of Equipment Activities and their IDs. The bookmark token in the response can be used in the query parameter in the subsequent API call to obtain the set of remaining records. You can find more details on bookmarks <a href=\"/#tag/Bookmarks\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">here</a>.  \n\n\n- **Step 2: <mark style=\"background-color:#00d084\" class=\"has-inline-color has-white-color\"> GET </mark> - <a href=\"/#operation/GetLayers\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Get the list of Layers for an Equipment Activity ID</a>**  \nThis will return the list of Layers for a single Equipment Activity task.  \n-- **API Call: {{BaseURL}}**/tasks/**{{OrgId}}**/layers?equipmentActivityId=**{{EquipmentActivityId}}**  \n-- **Path Variable:** Org ID  \n-- **Query Parameter:** Equipment Activity ID (obtained from Step 1 response)  \n-- **Response:** A successful GET request will result in 200 OK status code along with the response body that includes a list of Layers and their IDs.  \n\n\n- **Step 3: <mark style=\"background-color:#00d084\" class=\"has-inline-color has-white-color\"> GET </mark> - <a href=\"/#operation/GetLayerSamples\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Get the list of Samples on a Layer</a>**  \nThis will return the list of Samples (i.e. locations) along with the Sensors and associated values for a single Layer.  \n-- **API Call: {{BaseURL}}**/tasks/**{{OrgId}}**/layers/**{{layerId}}**/samples  \n-- **Path Variables:** Org ID, Layer ID (obtained from Step 2 response)  \n-- **Response:** A successful GET request will result in a 200 status code along with the Samples and Sensor values associated with the Layer."
    },
    {
      "name": "Send Prescription To a PTx Trimble Display",
      "x-displayName": "Send Prescription To a PTx Trimble Display",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  Prescriptions can be sent to FarmENGAGE and/or directly to a field device by using the following steps.<br />1. POST Initiate Prescription import<br />2. PATCH Upload zipped file for Prescription import\n</div>\n\n- **Step 1: <mark style=\"background-color:#0693e3\" class=\"has-inline-color has-white-color\">POST</mark> - <a href=\"/#operation/InitiatePrescriptionImport\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Initiate Prescription Import</a>**  \nUse this endpoint to create a prescription record with the prescription information.  \n-- **API Call:** **{{BaseURL}}**/prescriptions/**{{OrgId}}**/rx/importjob/  \n-- **Path Parameter:** Org ID  \n-- **Response:** A successful POST request will result in the 200 status code along with the Job ID in the response body.\n\n- **Step 2: <mark style=\"background-color:#fcb900\" class=\"has-inline-color has-white-color\">PATCH</mark> - <a href=\"/#operation/UploadPrescriptionFile\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Upload zip file for Prescription import</a>**  \nUse this endpoint to upload the Prescription zipped file to FarmENGAGE and/or directly to a field device.  \n-- **API Call: {{BaseURL}}**/prescriptions/**{{OrgId}}**/rx/importjob/**{{jobId}}**  \n-- **Path Parameter:** Org ID, Job ID (obtained from Step 1 response)  \n-- **Response:** When the PATCH request goes through it will result in a 204 No Content status code with empty response body."
    },
    {
      "name": "Send Fields to FarmENGAGE",
      "x-displayName": "Send Fields to FarmENGAGE",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  Send Fields to the FarmENGAGE using the below endpoint. These Fields can then be routed to PTx Trimble displays.\n</div>\n\n- **<mark style=\"background-color:#0693e3\" class=\"has-inline-color has-white-color\">POST</mark> - <a href=\"/#operation/CreateField\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Create a Field</a>**  \nThis endpoint will create a Field in FarmENGAGE.  \n-- **API Call:** **{{BaseURL}**}/resources/**{{OrgId}**}/fields/  \n-- **Path Variable:** Org ID  \n-- **Response:** A successful POST request will result in the 200 OK status code with the Field ID and entity links in the response body. These links can be used to make API calls associated with the newly created Field. You can find more details on the entity links [here][1].\n\n [1]: /#tag/Links"
    },
    {
      "name": "Send Boundaries to FarmENGAGE",
      "x-displayName": "Send Boundaries to FarmENGAGE",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  Send Boundaries to FarmENGAGE using the below endpoint. These Boundaries can then be routed to PTx Trimble displays.\n</div>\n\n- **<mark style=\"background-color:#0693e3\" class=\"has-inline-color has-white-color\">POST</mark> - <a href=\"/#operation/CreateBoundary\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Create a Boundary</a>**  \nThis endpoint can be used to create a new Boundary.  \n-- **API Call:** **{{BaseURL}**}/resources/**{{OrgId}}**/boundaries  \n-- **Path Variable:** Org ID  \n-- **Request Body:** The field ID would be the ID of the field in which you want to create a new Boundary.  \n-- **Response:** A successful POST request will result in the 200 OK status code along with the Boundary ID and entity links in the response body. These links can be used to access the endpoints associated with the newly created Boundary. You can find more details on the entity links [here][1].\n\n [1]: /#tag/Links"
    },
    {
      "name": "Send Guidance Lines to FarmENGAGE",
      "x-displayName": "Send Guidance Lines to FarmENGAGE",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  Send Guidance Lines to FarmENGAGE using the below endpoint. These Guidance Lines can then be routed to PTx Trimble displays.\n</div>\n\n- **<mark style=\"background-color:#0693e3\" class=\"has-inline-color has-white-color\">POST</mark> <a href=\"/#operation/CreateGuidanceline\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Create a Guidance Line</a>**  \nThis endpoint will create a new Guidance Line in FarmENGAGE.  \n-- **API Call:** **{{BaseURL}**}/resources/**{{OrgId}}**/guidancelines  \n-- **Path Variable:** Org ID  \n-- **Request Body:** The field ID would be the ID of the field in which you want to create a new Guidance Pattern.  \n-- **Response:** A successful POST request will result in the 200 OK status code along with the Guidance Line ID and entity links in the response body. These links can be used to access the endpoints associated with the newly created Guidance Line. You can find more details on the entity links [here][1].\n\n [1]: /#tag/Links"
    },
    {
      "name": "Sample-Code-Overview",
      "x-displayName": "Overview",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  Partners and potential partners can easily integrate with our API using pre-built sample code for essential workflows. Whether you want to streamline prescription posting, retrieve equipment activity data or efficiently manage resources like fields, boundaries, and guidance lines, our Sample Code makes integration simple and easy. Languages covered include Java, Javascript, and Python.\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "Link to Sample Code",
      "x-displayName": "Link to Sample Code",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  Sample code can be found here - Coming Soon\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "Overview-and-When-to-Use-1",
      "x-displayName": "Overview and When to Use",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  Nearly all API partners are set up to use the Authorization Code Grant for Authentication. Unless you are informed otherwise, this is how your API Connection will be set up and you should use these authentication and authorization instructions (the Client Credentials Grant will not work for your API setup).<br /><br />This configuration option utilizes user-level authorization. This authentication applies when multiple users log into the 3rd party application connected via API (your application) and every user should have access to the different organizations that they individually have access to through different FarmENGAGE logins.<br /><br /><strong>Definition of Variables</strong>\n</div><figure class=\"wp-block-table\">\n\n<table><tr>\n  <td class=\"has-text-align-left\" data-align=\"left\">\n    <strong>Variables</strong>\n  </td>\n  \n  <td class=\"has-text-align-left\" data-align=\"left\">\n    <strong>Definition</strong>\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td class=\"has-text-align-left\" data-align=\"left\">\n    AGCO ID {{Env Auth root}}\n  </td>\n  \n  <td class=\"has-text-align-left\" data-align=\"left\">\n    Production authentication - <a href=\"https://onelogin.agcocorp.com/051b9332-1f85-46f9-87be-a6ea3157fd86/\">https://onelogin.agcocorp.com/051b9332-1f85-46f9-87be-a6ea3157fd86/</a>\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td class=\"has-text-align-left\" data-align=\"left\">\n    FarmENGAGE API {{Env Data root}}\n  </td>\n  \n  <td class=\"has-text-align-left\" data-align=\"left\">\n    Production data - <a href=\"https://api.farmengage.com/prod/externalApi/3.0\">https://api.farmengage.com/prod/externalApi/3.0</a>\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td class=\"has-text-align-left\" data-align=\"left\">\n    {{yourAGCOClientId}}\n  </td>\n  \n  <td class=\"has-text-align-left\" data-align=\"left\">\n    The GUID (unique identifier) provided by PTx that is assigned to your application\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td class=\"has-text-align-left\" data-align=\"left\">\n    {{yourAGCOSecret}}\n  </td>\n  \n  <td class=\"has-text-align-left\" data-align=\"left\">\n    The secret value that pairs with your AGCO Client ID\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td class=\"has-text-align-left\" data-align=\"left\">\n    {{authenticationCallbackURL}}\n  </td>\n  \n  <td class=\"has-text-align-left\" data-align=\"left\">\n    The URL that users should be returned to from OAuth login at AGCO ID (must be an exact match to a URL in the list of valid authenticationCallback URLs you provide)\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td class=\"has-text-align-left\" data-align=\"left\">\n    {{authorizationRedirectURL}}\n  </td>\n  \n  <td class=\"has-text-align-left\" data-align=\"left\">\n    The URL that users should be redirected to after authorizing Organizations for data access at <a href=\"https://www.farmengage.com/\">www.farmengage.com</a> (must be an exact match to a URL in the list of valid authorizationRedirectURLs you provide)\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td class=\"has-text-align-left\" data-align=\"left\">\n    {{AuthCode}}\n  </td>\n  \n  <td class=\"has-text-align-left\" data-align=\"left\">\n    The code generated by the AGCO ID system that you can exchange for an access, refresh and ID token from AGCO ID.<br /><strong>This code may only be used once and expires after 10 minutes.</strong>\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td class=\"has-text-align-left\" data-align=\"left\">\n    {{accessToken}}\n  </td>\n  \n  <td class=\"has-text-align-left\" data-align=\"left\">\n    The JWT token that is used to access data endpoints.<br /><strong>The access token has a 1 hour expiration.</strong>\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td class=\"has-text-align-left\" data-align=\"left\">\n    {{idToken}}\n  </td>\n  \n  <td class=\"has-text-align-left\" data-align=\"left\">\n    The JWT token contains additional information about the user who was authenticated in AGCO ID.\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td class=\"has-text-align-left\" data-align=\"left\">\n    {{refreshToken}}\n  </td>\n  \n  <td class=\"has-text-align-left\" data-align=\"left\">\n    The token has a 7-day expiration that can be exchanged for a new access token.\n  </td>\n</tr></table></figure>"
    },
    {
      "name": "Authentication",
      "x-displayName": "Authentication",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  In order for your application to access data within an Organization, the FarmENGAGE user must approve your application in an Authorization step, but in order to discover if a user has authorized your application you need to go through an OAuth process to gain access to the data that is scoped to that user.</div>\n\n#### **User Authorization Code**\n\n#### Step 1\n\nThe first step of the OAuth process is to send the user to log into AGCO's identity management system in order to obtain an authorization code. **This code will be valid for 10 minutes.**\n\n#### URL\n\nUse this GET call to redirect the user to AGCO ID.\n\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>{{Env Auth root}}/oauth2/v2.0/authorize?scope=openid profile email offline_access {{yourAGCOClientId}}&response_type=code&redirect_uri={{authenticationCallbackUrl}}&client_id={{yourAGCOClientId}}&p=b2c_1a_signin_ptx</code></pre>\n\n#### Step 2\n\nAfter the user logs into AGCO ID they will be returned to your application via the following URL:\n\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>{{authenticationCallbackUrl}}?code={{AuthCode}}</code></pre>"
    },
    {
      "name": "Authentication Token API",
      "x-displayName": "Authentication Token API",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  This API can be used for authentication from a third party client application or a web service to obtain an access token to use for subsequent method calls as described in the Common authentication token. This API also returns an ID for identification and a refresh token for re-authentication after the access token expires. <strong>The authentication token is valid for 1 hour and the refresh token is valid for 9 days. The refresh token is a single-use token that becomes invalid after use.</strong>\n</div>\n\n#### URL\n\nThis URL should be used to obtain an authentication token and the refresh token.\n\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>POST {{Env Auth root}}/oauth2/v2.0/token?p=b2c_1a_signin_ptx</code></pre>\n\n#### Input Example\n\nThe following is an example of the parameters to help illustrate the definition. The string of characters after the word Basic would be the result of base 64 encoding **{{yourAGCOClientId}}:{{yourAGCOSecret}}** which you would replace with your own values.\n\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>POST: https://onelogin.agcocorp.com/051b9332-1f85-46f9-87be-a6ea3157fd86/oauth2/v2.0/token?p=b2c_1a_signin_ptx\nContent-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded\nAuthorization: Basic TXlQcm….\ncode=sd3ds…&client_id=e3rdfF…&redirect_uri=https://mydomain.com/oauthreturn</code></pre>\n\nThe header and request body values are defined in the following tables.\n\n#### **Header Values**\n\nThis web service expects you to post a URL- Form- Encoded string in the request body, containing the following fields in the header:<figure class=\"wp-block-table\">\n\n<table><tr>\n  <td>\n    <strong>Attribute</strong>\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    <strong>Description</strong>\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    <strong>Values</strong>\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    <strong>Required</strong>\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td>\n    Authorization\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    Basic Auth using Base64 encoded value of provided <strong>ClientID:ClientSecret</strong>\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    Basic {Encoded value goes here}\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    Y\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td>\n    Content-Type\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    Specifies the request content type\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    application/x-www-form-urlencoded\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    Y\n  </td>\n</tr></table></figure> \n\n**Request Body Values**\n\nThis web service expects you to post a URL- Form- Encoded string in the request body, containing the following fields:<figure class=\"wp-block-table\">\n\n<table><tr>\n  <td>\n    <strong>Attribute</strong>\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    <strong>Description</strong>\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    <strong>Values</strong>\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    <strong>Required</strong>\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td>\n    code\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    The authorization code returned from the OAuth process\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    {{AuthCode}}\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    Y\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td>\n    client_id\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    The GUID provided to you\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    {{yourAGCOClientId}}\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    Y\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td>\n    redirect_uri\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    An exact match to one of the URLs provided to PTx Trimble by you to return to your app after logging in.\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    {{authenticationCallbackUrl}}\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    Y\n  </td>\n</tr></table></figure> \n\n#### **Response**\n\nThis service acknowledges with an HTTP code 200 for success (OK) and all other HTTP codes for failure.&nbsp;\n\nIn addition to the 200 HTTP code, the web service responds with a JSON formatted document with the following fields to provide either confirmation of the receipt or an error:<figure class=\"wp-block-table\">\n\n<table><tr>\n  <td>\n    <strong>Attribute</strong>\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    <strong>Description</strong>\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    <strong>Values</strong>\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td>\n    access_token\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    The security token that is used on subsequent requests.\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    This token will be a Base64URL-encoded string generated with each new POST to this endpoint.\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td>\n    id_token\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    JWT token to provide additional information about the user.\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    This token will be a Base64URL-encoded string generated with each new POST to this endpoint.\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td>\n    token_type\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    Identifier of what type of token has been returned.\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    Will always be “Bearer”\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td>\n    not_before\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    Unix timestamp of when the token becomes valid.\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    Security feature to prevent use of the token before a certain time. You can ignore this value as the token will not be valid until you receive it.\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td>\n    expires_in\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    Time in seconds until expiration.\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    Returns “3600”.&nbsp;&nbsp;<br />Each call to the endpoint results in a new token lasting 60 minutes.<br />Please cache and reuse the token for calls within 60 minutes of the last authentication.\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td>\n    expires_on\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    Unix timestamp of when the token expires.\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    Security feature to prevent use of the token after a certain time. You can ignore this value as you can calculate the expiration time using the expires_in value.\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td>\n    resource\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    The resource that the token is for.\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    This will match your AGCO Client ID.\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td>\n    id_token_expires_in\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    Time in seconds until the ID token expires.\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    Returns “3600”.&nbsp;&nbsp;<br />Each call to the endpoint results in a new ID token lasting 60 minutes.<br />Please cache and reuse the ID token for calls within 60 minutes of the last authentication.\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td>\n    profile_info\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    Contains basic information about the user this token was generated for.\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    Base64URL-encoded\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td>\n    scope\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    The scopes that the token is valid for.\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    Scopes are permissions that the token has. This will be a space-delimited list of scopes that the token is valid for.\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td>\n    refresh_token\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    Token to exchange for a new access token and refresh token.\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    This token will be a string generated with each new POST to this endpoint.\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td>\n    error\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    The Error title of the error being shown.\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    &nbsp;\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td>\n    error_description\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    Error description to help understand the error provided.\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    &nbsp;\n  </td>\n</tr></table></figure> \n\n#### **Response example (tokens truncated)**\n\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>Content-Type: application/json; charset=utf-8{\n    \"access_token\": \"eyJhbGci...\",\n    \"id_token\": \"eyJhbGci...\",\n    \"token_type\": \"Bearer\",\n    \"not_before\": 1772051265,\n    \"expires_in\": 3600,\n    \"expires_on\": 1772054865,\n    \"resource\": \"8a4cf2a4-40a0-...\",\n    \"id_token_expires_in\": 3600,\n    \"profile_info\": \"eyJ2ZX...\",\n    \"scope\": \"8a4cf2a4-40a0-... offline_access openid\",\n    \"refresh_token\": \"eyJraWQ...\",\n    \"refresh_token_expires_in\": 1209600\n}</code></pre>"
    },
    {
      "name": "Refresh Authentication Token API",
      "x-displayName": "Refresh Authentication Token API",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n</div>\n\n#### **URL**\n\nUse the following URL to obtain a refresh token once the authentication token expires.\n\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>POST  {{Env Auth root}}/oauth/token?p=b2c_1a_signin_ptx</code></pre>\n\n#### **Input example**\n\nThe following is an example of the parameters to help illustrate the definition. The string of characters after the word **Basic** would be the result of base 64 encoding **MyProvidedClientId:MyClientSecret** are replaced with your own values.\n\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>POST: https://onelogin.agcocorp.com/051b9332-1f85-46f9-87be-a6ea3157fd86/oauth2/v2.0/token?p=b2c_1a_signin_ptx\nContent-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded\nAuthorization: Basic TXlQcm….\ngrant_type=refresh_token\n&refresh_token=sd3ds…\n&tenantDomain=agcocorp.com</code></pre>\n\n#### **Header Values**\n\nThe web service expects you to post a URL- Form- Encoded string in the body, containing the following header values:<figure class=\"wp-block-table\">\n\n<table><tr>\n  <td>\n    <strong>Attribute</strong>\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    <strong>Description</strong>\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    <strong>Values</strong>\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    <strong>Required</strong>\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td>\n    Authorization\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    Basic Auth using Base64 encoded value of provided <strong>{{yourAGCOClientId}}:{{yourAGCOSecret}}</strong>\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    Basic {Encoded value goes here}\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    Y\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td>\n    Content-Type\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    Specifies the request content type.\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    application/x-www-form-urlencoded\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    Y\n  </td>\n</tr></table></figure> \n\n#### **Body Values**\n\nThe web service expects you to post a URL-Form-Encoded string in the body, containing the following fields:<figure class=\"wp-block-table\">\n\n<table><tr>\n  <td>\n    <strong>Attribute</strong>\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    <strong>Description</strong>\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    <strong>Values</strong>\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    <strong>Required</strong>\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td>\n    grant_type\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    Required value to identify authentication type.\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    refresh_token\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    Y\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td>\n    refresh_token\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    The refresh code returned from the Authentication Token [link inserted here] endpoint.\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    {{RefreshToken}}\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    Y\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td>\n    tenantDomain\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    <strong>*Required value</strong>\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    agcocorp.com\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    Y\n  </td>\n</tr></table></figure> \n\n#### **Response**\n\nThe service sends an acknowledgement with HTTP code 200 for success (OK) and any other HTTP code for failure.\n\nIn addition to the HTTP 200 code, the web service responds with a JSON formatted document with the following fields to provide either confirmation of the receipt or an error:<figure class=\"wp-block-table\">\n\n<table><tr>\n  <td>\n    <strong>Attribute</strong>\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    <strong>Description</strong>\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    <strong>Values</strong>\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td>\n    access_token\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    The security token that needs to be used on subsequent requests.\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    This token will be a long string generated with each new POST to this endpoint.\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td>\n    token_type\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    Identifier of what type of token must be returned.\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    Will always be “bearer”\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td>\n    expires_in\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    Time in seconds until expiration.\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    Will return 3600.&nbsp; Each call to the endpoint will result in a new token lasting 60 minutes, please cache and reuse the token for calls within 60 minutes of the last authentication.\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td>\n    id_token\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    JWT token to provide additional information about the user.\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    This token will be a long string generated with each new POST to this endpoint.\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td>\n    refresh_token\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    Token to exchange for a new access token and refresh token.\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    This token will be a string generated with each new POST to this endpoint.\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td>\n    error\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    Error title\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    &nbsp;\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td>\n    error_description\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    Error description to help understand the error provided.\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    &nbsp;\n  </td>\n</tr></table></figure> \n\n#### **Response example (tokens truncated)**\n\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>Content-Type: application/json; charset=utf-8{\n    \"access_token\": \"eyJhbGci...\",\n    \"id_token\": \"eyJhbGci...\",\n    \"token_type\": \"Bearer\",\n    \"not_before\": 1772051265,\n    \"expires_in\": 3600,\n    \"expires_on\": 1772054865,\n    \"resource\": \"8a4cf2a4-40a0-...\",\n    \"id_token_expires_in\": 3600,\n    \"profile_info\": \"eyJ2ZX...\",\n    \"scope\": \"8a4cf2a4-40a0-... offline_access openid\",\n    \"refresh_token\": \"eyJraWQ...\",\n    \"refresh_token_expires_in\": 1209600\n}</code></pre>"
    },
    {
      "name": "Common Authentication Token",
      "x-displayName": "Common Authentication Token",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  All REST calls made available by the Connected Farm data center will require proper authentication. To achieve this, an AGCO ID access token must be passed to validate that the caller has permission. All subsequent calls are validated by the AGCO ID service and the access token should be prefixed with Bearer in the Authorization header. <br />The following is an example of the parameters to help illustrate the definition:\n</div>\n\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>GET:\nhttps:&#47;&#47;api.farmengage.com/prod/externalApi/3.0/config/organizations\nAuthorization: Bearer \neyJ0eXAiOiJK....</code></pre>"
    },
    {
      "name": "Overview-and-When-to-Use-2",
      "x-displayName": "Overview and When to Use",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  This configuration only applies to specific API partners. You would be informed if you are set up to use the <strong>Client Credentials Grant</strong>. If you are not setup to use the <strong>Client Credentials Grant</strong> process you can skip this section.<br /><br />This configuration option utilizes application-level authorization.  This authentication and authorization applies when only a single entity logs into the 3rd party application connected via API (your application) and every user should have access to the same authorized organizations in FarmENGAGE.\n</div>\n\n**Definition of variables**<figure class=\"wp-block-table\">\n\n<table><tr>\n  <td>\n    <strong>Variables</strong>\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    <strong>Definition</strong>\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td>\n    AGCO ID {{Env Auth root}}\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    Production authentication - <a href=\"https://onelogin.agcocorp.com/051b9332-1f85-46f9-87be-a6ea3157fd86/\">https://onelogin.agcocorp.com/051b9332-1f85-46f9-87be-a6ea3157fd86/</a>\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td>\n    {{yourAGCOClientId}}\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    The GUID (unique identifier) provided by PTx Trimble that is assigned to your application.\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td>\n    {{yourAGCOSecret}}\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    The secret provided by PTx Trimble that is assigned to your application.\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td>\n    {{accessToken}}\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    The JWT token that is used to access data endpoints.<br /><strong>The access token has a 1 hour expiration.</strong>\n  </td>\n</tr></table></figure>"
    },
    {
      "name": "Authentication-Token-API-2",
      "x-displayName": "Authentication Token API",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  This API can be used for authentication from a third party client application or a web service to obtain an access token to use for subsequent method calls as described in the Common authentication token. This API also returns an ID for identification and a refresh token for re-authentication after the access token expires. <strong>The authentication token is valid for 1 hour and the refresh token is valid for 9 days. The refresh token is a single-use token that becomes invalid after use.</strong>\n</div>\n\n#### URL\n\nThis URL should be used to obtain an authentication token and the refresh token.\n\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>POST {{Env Auth root}}/oauth2/v2.0/token?p=b2c_1a_signin_ptx</code></pre>\n\n#### Input Example\n\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>POST: https://onelogin.agcocorp.com/051b9332-1f85-46f9-87be-a6ea3157fd86/oauth2/v2.0/token?p=b2c_1a_signin_ptx\nContent-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded\nscope=https://onelogin.agcocorp.com/991ec121-2446-47d0-a108-fd35c79cc441/.default\n&client_id=...\n&client_secret=...</code></pre>\n\nThe header and request body values are defined in the following tables.\n\n#### **Header Values**\n\nThis web service expects you to post a URL- Form- Encoded string in the request body, containing the following fields in the header:<figure class=\"wp-block-table\">\n\n<table><tr>\n  <td>\n    <strong>Attribute</strong>\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    <strong>Description</strong>\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    <strong>Values</strong>\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    <strong>Required</strong>\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td>\n    Content-Type\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    Specifies the request content type\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    application/x-www-form-urlencoded\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    Y\n  </td>\n</tr></table></figure> \n\n#### **Parameter Values**\n\nThe web service expects the following fields as query string parameters:<figure class=\"wp-block-table\">\n\n<table><tr>\n  <td>\n    <strong>Attribute</strong>\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    <strong>Description</strong>\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    <strong>Values</strong>\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    <strong>Required</strong>\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td>\n    scope\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    The scope of the access request. This should be in the format of {resource}/.default\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    https://onelogin.agcocorp.com/991ec121-2446-47d0-a108-fd35c79cc441/.default\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    Y\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td>\n    client_id\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    The unique identifier for the client application that is registered in the authentication system.\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    {{yourAGCOClientId}}\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    Y\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td>\n    client_secret\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    The secret value that pairs with your AGCO Client ID\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    {{yourAGCOSecret}}\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    Y\n  </td>\n</tr></table></figure> \n\n#### **Response**\n\nThis service acknowledges with an HTTP code 200 for success (OK) and all other HTTP codes for failure.\n\nIn addition to the 200 HTTP code, the web service responds with a JSON formatted document with the following fields to provide either confirmation of the receipt or an error:<figure class=\"wp-block-table\">\n\n<table><tr>\n  <td>\n    <strong>Attribute</strong>\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    <strong>Description</strong>\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    <strong>Values</strong>\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td>\n    access_token\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    The security token that is used on subsequent requests.\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    This token will be a long string generated with each new POST to this endpoint.\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td>\n    token_type\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    Identifier of what type of token has been returned.\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    Will always be “Bearer”.\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td>\n    not_before\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    Security feature to prevent use of the token before a certain time. You can ignore this value as the token will not be valid until you receive it.\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    Will always be “Bearer”.\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td>\n    expires_in\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    Time in seconds until expiration.\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    Returns “3600”.&nbsp;&nbsp;<br />Each call to the endpoint results in a new token lasting 60 minutes.<br />Please cache and reuse the token for calls within 60 minutes of the last authentication.\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td>\n    expires_on\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    Unix timestamp of when the token expires.\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    Security feature to prevent use of the token after a certain time. You can ignore this value as you can calculate the expiration time using the expires_in value.\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td>\n    resource\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    The resource that the token is valid for.\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    This will match your AGCO Client ID.\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td>\n    error\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    Error title\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    &nbsp;\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td>\n    error_description\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    Error description to help understand the error provided.\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    &nbsp;\n  </td>\n</tr></table></figure> \n\n#### **Response example (tokens truncated)**\n\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>Content-Type: application/json; charset=utf-8\n{\n    \"access_token\": \"eyJhbGciOi..\",\n    \"token_type\": \"Bearer\",\n    \"not_before\": 1772052595,\n    \"expires_in\": 3600,\n    \"expires_on\": 1772056195,\n    \"resource\": \"991ec121-2446-...\"\n}</code></pre>"
    },
    {
      "name": "Authorization of Organizations",
      "x-displayName": "Authorization of Organizations",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  <strong>In order to gain access to an Organization’s data, a user of that Organization must authorize your application to do so. This is accomplished through an OAuth process, where the user will be directed to a FarmENGAGE website. Here, the user is required to sign in, approve your application and select which Organizations to approve for access.</strong>\n</div>\n\n### Step 1\n\nFrom your application, or via another process of your choice, redirect the user that would be approving your application to the following URL:\n\n##### **URL for Authorization Code Grant**\n\n[https://www.farmengage.com/ThirdPartyAccess/ThirdPartyAuthorizationRedirect?clientid={{yourAGCOClientId}}&redirectionUrl={{authorizationRedirectUrl}}&IsAgcoId=true][1]\n\n##### **URL for Client Credentials Grant**\n\n[https://www.farmengage.com/ThirdPartyAccess/ThirdPartyAuthorizationRedirect?clientid={{yourAGCOClientId}}&IsAgcoId=true][2]\n\n### Step 2\n\nUsers who are not currently logged in are directed to PTx Trimble’s login service for [www.farmengage.com][3].<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\">\n\n[<img src=\"/images/farmengage_login_step2.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-28738\" />][4]</figure> \n\n### Step 3\n\nThe logged-in user is presented with an Authorization page that uses the logo provided to FarmENGAGE as part of the Authorization setup.<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\">\n\n[<img src=\"/images/farmengage_login_step3.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-28733\" />][5]</figure> \n\n### Step 4\n\nOnce your application is authorized for that user, the user will be presented with a list of Organizations to which they have access and can select the Organizations to which they want your application to have access as well.&nbsp; Selecting a FarmENGAGE Advisor Organization provides access to all the child Organizations that the logged- in user has access to for that Advisor Organization.<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\">\n\n[<img src=\"/images/farmengage_login_step4.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-28734\" />][6]</figure> \n\n### Step 5\n\n##### **This step only applicable for Authorization Code Grant**\n\nOnce the user hits the save button after selecting the Organizations, they will be redirected to the authorization redirect URL that you provided during setup of your application with FarmENGAGE.\n\n### Step 6\n\nOnce the user has authorized you to access their data, you can expect the following**:**\n\n#### **Below applies to Authorization Code Grant**\n\n- The **OrgIds** authorized for that user will appear in the GET **config/organizations** result set.  \n- The returned results will be scoped to the token for that user.&nbsp; It is your responsibility to use the proper user token for matching the user in your system and use the refresh token before it expires.  \n- If the refresh token expires before you use it to acquire a new token, your system will need to acquire a new User Authorization Code to exchange for a new access and refresh token.  \n- **User Authorization Code - Valid for 10 mins, Access Token - Valid for 1 hour, Refresh Token - Valid for 9 days**.\n\n#### **Below applies to Client Credentials Grant**\n\n- The **OrgIds** authorized for that user will appear in the GET **config/organizations** result set.  \n- The returned results will be scoped to the list of orgs authorized to be accessed by your application.  \n- When the access token expires you will need to call the Authentication Token endpoint again to obtain a new **_access_code_** to use with the APIs.  \n- **Access Token - Valid for 1 hour**.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n**_For each user that approves usage of their data, it is your responsibility to ensure that only the authorized user has access to the authorized data in your application._**\n\n [1]: https://www.trimbleag.com/ThirdPartyAccess/ThirdPartyAuthorizationRedirect?clientid={{yourAGCOClientId}}&redirectionUrl={{authorizationRedirectUrl}}\n [2]: https://www.trimbleag.com/ThirdPartyAccess/ThirdPartyAuthorizationRedirect?clientid={{yourAGCOClientId}}\n [3]: http://www.trimbleag.com\n [4]: /images/farmengage_login_step2.png\n [5]: \"/images/farmengage_login_step3.png\n [6]: \"/images/farmengage_login_step4.png"
    },
    {
      "name": "Organizations",
      "x-displayName": "Organizations",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  Use this method from a third-party client application or web service to obtain a list of approved organizations for the access token.  For each user that approves Organization data it is your responsibility to ensure that only that authorized user has access to that data in your application.\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "clients-farms-fields-overview",
      "x-displayName": "Overview",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  The Client, Farm, Field APIs enable users to create Clients, Farms, and Fields in other applications; share those with FarmENGAGE; and send them to connected PTx Trimble displays. Clients, Farms, and Fields from FarmENGAGE or PTx Trimble Displays can also be sent back to the other applications.\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "Clients",
      "x-displayName": "Clients",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  Clients are the highest level of the organization hierarchy for a Field. Clients contain Farms.\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "Farms",
      "x-displayName": "Farms",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  Farms are the middle level of the organization hierarchy for a Field. Farms are contained within Clients, and contain Fields.\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "Fields",
      "x-displayName": "Fields",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  Fields define a piece of ground and are used to organize the work that happens on that ground. Fields are contained within Farms. Fields contain Boundaries, Field Extents, Guidance Lines, Landmarks, Crop Seasons, Prescriptions, Files, and Tasks.\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "resources-overview",
      "x-displayName": "Overview",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  The Field Resources APIs enable users to create Field Extents, Boundaries, Guidance Lines, and Landmarks in other applications; share those with FarmENGAGE; and send them to connected PTx Trimble displays. Field Extents, Boundaries, Guidance Lines, and Landmarks from FarmENGAGE or PTx Trimble Displays can also be sent to other applications.\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "Field Extents",
      "x-displayName": "Field Extents",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  A Field Extent is a property of a field and is primarily used for record-keeping. On a PTx Trimble display Field Extents can be viewed, but not edited, using the Field Manager. In the FarmENGAGE web and mobile tools Field Extents can be viewed and edited from the Fields List. As Field Extents are properties of Fields, they share the same ID as the Field.\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "Boundaries",
      "x-displayName": "Boundaries",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  Boundaries are the functional extent of a field and are used for operational workflows. On a PTx Trimble display Boundaries can be viewed and edited using the Field Manager. On the web Boundaries are viewed from Landmarks page within a Crop Zone.\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "Guidance Lines",
      "x-displayName": "Guidance Lines",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  Guidance Line are a navigation aid used by precision ag displays to define where to drive in a field. Guidance Lines are contained within Fields.\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "Landmarks",
      "x-displayName": "Landmarks",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  Landmarks are features that are points of interest within a Field. Landmarks are contained within Fields.\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "LandmarkLines",
      "x-displayName": "LandmarkLines",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "Resource Files",
      "x-displayName": "Resource Files",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "cropZones-overview",
      "x-displayName": "Overview",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  Crop Zones are used to organize information about the crop being grown in a field in a particular year. Crop Zones include information about the crop, boundary for that crop, and what tasks occurred in relation to that crop in a particular growing season.\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "Master Crops",
      "x-displayName": "Master Crops",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  Master Crops represent crops that can assigned to be grown in a Crop Zone.\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "Crop Seasons",
      "x-displayName": "Crop Seasons",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  Crop Seasons represent the combination of a year and a Master Crop being grown in a field within a particular year.\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "Crop Zones",
      "x-displayName": "Crop Zones",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  Crop Zones represent a Crop Season for a Field. Crop Zones are contained within Fields. Equipment Activities and Crop Zone Activities are contained within Crop Zones.\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "Crop Zone Extents",
      "x-displayName": "Crop Zone Extents",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  A Crop Zone Extent is a property of a Crop Zone and represents the boundary for a Crop Zone. When created in the FarmENGAGE UI, Crop Zone Extents will initially be an exact match of the Field Extent and can then be modified by the user. As Crop Zone Extents are properties of Crop Zones, they share the same ID as the Crop Zone.\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "vehicles-implements-devices-overview",
      "x-displayName": "Overview",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  The Vehicles, Implements, Devices APIs are used to create and capture information about equipment that is used to complete work. This information may be associated with jobs that are completed (as available from the EquipmentActivity or CropZoneActivity APIs) in a Crop Zone. Further, The Devices APIs can enable sending recommendations directly to the devices that will execute those recommendations in the field (using the Prescriptions APIs).\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "Devices",
      "x-displayName": "Devices",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  Devices represent displays that are used for in-field operational workflows and are contained within Organizations.\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "Vehicles",
      "x-displayName": "Vehicles",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  Vehicles represent machinery that is used to complete fieldwork. Vehicles have a Manufacturer, Equipment Type, and may optionally be included in Equipment Groups. Devices may be assigned to Vehicles.\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "Vehicle Types",
      "x-displayName": "Vehicle Types",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  Vehicle Types are assigned to Vehicles and are used to account for the general vehicle function. Example Vehicle Types include “Combine”, “Spayer”, “Tractor-4WD” and “Generic”.\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "Equipment Groups",
      "x-displayName": "Equipment Groups",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  Equipment Groups are an optional classification that can be created and apply to Vehicles. These assignments could be based on Vehicles that serve the same function, are in the same region, or for any other reason the user chooses.\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "Equipment Manufacturers",
      "x-displayName": "Equipment Manufacturers",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  Equipment Manufacturers are applied to Vehicles and represent the maker of the Vehicle.\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "Implements",
      "x-displayName": "Implements",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  An Implement represents an equipment that is used to execute work in the field. Implements may optionally include Operation Type and/or Equipment Group.\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "contacts-overview",
      "x-displayName": "Overview",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  The Contacts APIs enable users to create Contacts and Operator groups in other applications; share those with FarmENGAGE; and send them to connected PTx Trimble displays. Contacts and Operator Groups from FarmENGAGE can also be sent to other applications.\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "Contacts",
      "x-displayName": "Contacts",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  Contacts represent people that are associated with the running of an operation. Contact information can include detail such as contact detail,  whether the contact is an Equipment Operator, and whether the person has PTx Trimble Display access when Operator Sign-in is on for an Org.\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "Operator Groups",
      "x-displayName": "Operator Groups",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  Operator Groups are an optional classification that can be created and apply to Contacts. These assignments could be based on Contacts that perform the same function, are in the same region, or for any other reason the users choose.\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "management-zone-overview",
      "x-displayName": "Overview",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  The Management Zone APIs are used for managing spatial zones. These zones may be used as part of field management practices such as the creation and application of a variable rate prescription.\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "Management Zones",
      "x-displayName": "Management Zones",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "Management Zone Geometries",
      "x-displayName": "Management Zone Geometries",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "prescriptions-overview",
      "x-displayName": "Overview",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  The Prescriptions APIs allow users to send prescriptions from partner applications to FarmENGAGE and, if desired, directly to a field device.\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "Prescriptions",
      "x-displayName": "Prescriptions",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  Prescriptions represent a recommendation file. <br /><br /><strong>Prescription file structure</strong><br /><br />- The zip file should contain at least one set of .shp, .dbf, and .shx files with the polygons and rates. The projection for the prescription shapefiles should be GCS WGS84.<br />- The user does not need to include a .prj file in the zip file. The polygons should only have one exterior cycle and may contain one or more interior cycles (holes).<br />- The .dbf should have at least one numeric column of data that contains the corresponding rates for each polygon. Multiple sets of shapefiles may be included in a single .zip file, but all the .dbf files must have the same rate column name for the display to recognize the rate column.<br /><br /><strong>Steps to upload the Prescription</strong><br /><br />1. Use the Prescription POST endpoint to create a prescription record with the prescription information. Optionally, specify a device GUID to send to a Device.<br /> - If specifying a device, you can view devices in your account from the Devices endpoint.<br /> - If there are no Devices in your account, you can create a sample Device for testing by using the Devices POST endpoint and any 10 digit ID.<br /><br />2. Use the Prescription PATCH endpoint to attach the prescription file to the prescription record. The Job ID from the response of the Prescription POST needs to be specified as the path parameter. The path to the zipped shapefile should be included in the request body.<br /><br />3. Use the Prescription GET Import Status endpoint to check the status of the upload. The Job ID from the response of the Prescription POST needs to be specified as the path parameter. The response will include \"Finished\" if the upload was successful.<br /><br />4. Use Prescription GET Send Status to check the status of the upload to a Device. The Job ID from the response of the Prescription POST needs to be specified as the path parameter. The response will include \"Pending\" if sending to a sample Device and \"Sent\" if sending to a real Device that is connected and receives the Prescription.\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "workorders-overview",
      "x-displayName": "Overview",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  The Work Orders API enables users to plan, assign, and communicate jobs to be completed across the farm. Work Orders can remotely preconfigure Precision-IQ Display tasks or may be completed manually.<br /><br />Work Orders are associated with Crop Zones.\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "Work Orders",
      "x-displayName": "Work Orders",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  Note that when updating Work Order status using the PUT endpoint the status can only be changed from \"Planned\" to \"Done\".\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "tasks-overview",
      "x-displayName": "Overview",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  The Tasks APIs enable users to forward job data from devices and FarmENGAGE to 3rd parties.\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "Equipment Activities",
      "x-displayName": "Equipment Activities",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  The Equipment Activity endpoints provide detailed information on tasks (i.e. in-field jobs such as planting, fertilizing, spraying, or harvesting) created from precision ag displays. This includes tasks from PTx Trimble displays and other equipment manufacturer display data that are in a FarmENGAGE account. The GET Equipment Activity endpoint returns a list of all tasks in that account along with their respective Equipment Activity IDs. The Equipment Activity IDs can then be used to access the as-applied or sensor data associated with an Equipment Activity task through the Layers endpoints (see Layers).<br /><br />Within the optional Equipment Activity query parameters, the startDate and endDate parameters are based on the ending time for a task. Therefore, if the task end UTC is equal to or past the query parameter startDate UTC, we return the task. Likewise, if the task end UTC is equal to or before the query filter EndDate UTC, we return the task.<br />\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "Layers",
      "x-displayName": "Layers",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  The Layers endpoints provide access to the sensor data (including as-applied data) associated with Equipment Activity tasks. To access this data, you need to use the GET Equipment Activity endpoint from the previous section to get Equipment Activity tasks and IDs, and then use those IDs with the Layers endpoints.<br /><br />For a brief overview of how to use the Layers endpoint, see below.<br /><br /><strong>--</strong> <strong>GET the list of Layers</strong><br /> - This endpoint will return a list of Layers for an Equipment Activity task.<br /> - An Equipment Activity ID must be used in the query parameter to obtain the list of layers.<br /><br /><strong>--</strong> <strong>GET detail for a Layer</strong><br /> - This endpoint will return details about a single layer for an Equipment Activity task.<br /> - A Layer ID must be used in the query parameter to obtain the layer details.<br /><br /><strong>-- GET the list of sensors on a Layer</strong><br /> - This endpoint will return a list of Sensors for a Layer.<br /> - A Layer ID must be used in the query parameter to obtain the list.<br /><br /><strong>-- GET the list of samples on a Layer</strong><br /> - This endpoint will return a list of Samples and values for Sensors associated with a Layer.<br /> - A Layer ID must be used in the query parameter to obtain the list.\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "Operation Types",
      "x-displayName": "Operation Types",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  Operation Types represent the different types of operations for the Equipment Activities and Crop Zone Activities. These are generic for all Orgs. Operation examples would be “Spreading” or Spraying”.\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "Operation Subtypes",
      "x-displayName": "Operation Subtypes",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  Operation Subtypes represent the different types of operations subtypes for the Equipment Activities and Crop Zone Activities. These would be customized by individual users. Examples could be “First Spraying” or “Second Spraying”.\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "Crop Zone Activities",
      "x-displayName": "Crop Zone Activities",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  Crop Zone Activities represent manual field records that were created in the FarmENGAGE mobile or online application. Crop Zone Activities do not have machine coverage or as-applied data.\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "Files",
      "x-displayName": "Files",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  Task files from field devices that are stored in FarmENGAGE are available to be downloaded through the Files API. Files will be zip files with either an AgGPS (FMX/FMX+) or AgData (Precision-IQ) folder of files. Once downloaded these files may need to be combined and will need to be parsed using the PTx Trimble plugins for the AgGateway ADAPT framework. More information about ADAPT can be found at adaptframework.org.<br /><br />Note that the Files endpoint provides the same data that is available from the EquipmentActivity endpoints, but in an unprocessed and encrypted format.<br /><br /><strong>Retrieve list of files from devices</strong><br /><br />Use this resource to obtain a list of files that are associated with a given organization. Each file returned will contain metadata about the file, and an Id plus a URL that can be used to directly download the file.\n</div>\n\n**Download specific files**\n\nUse the **temporaryAccessUri** returned the FileManagement/v3/Files API response to download individual files."
    },
    {
      "name": "materials-overview",
      "x-displayName": "Overview",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  The Materials APIs allow users to create, export, and track different inputs that are associated with applications in a Crop Zone.\n</div>\n\n&nbsp;"
    },
    {
      "name": "Materials",
      "x-displayName": "Materials",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  Materials represent different inputs that are applied to Crop Zones. Materials type examples include chemical, fertilizer, and seed. Material details could include information such as form, rate, and manufacturer.\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "Common-materials-overview",
      "x-displayName": "Overview",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  The Common Materials are the primary list of stored materials.\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "Common Materials",
      "x-displayName": "Common Materials",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  Common Material endpoints allow users to search for materials from the primary list of stored materials. Users can then create a new material in their organization from the Common Material using the Create a Chemical, Create a Fertilizer, or Create a Seed endpoint found under the Materials API.\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "inventory-overview",
      "x-displayName": "Overview",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  The Inventory APIs are used for record-keeping purposes and enable users to track current material inventory and create new material inventory.\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "Purchases",
      "x-displayName": "Purchases",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  Purchases are used to track material purchases and will impact materials inventory.\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "Balances",
      "x-displayName": "Balances",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  Balances represent current material inventory for a specific crop year.\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "commodities-overview",
      "x-displayName": "Overview",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  The Commodities API enables users to manage harvest storage locations, contracts, and storage transactions.\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "Contracts",
      "x-displayName": "Contracts",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "Contract Types",
      "x-displayName": "Contract Types",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "Customers",
      "x-displayName": "Customers",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "Storage Locations",
      "x-displayName": "Storage Locations",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "Storage Transactions",
      "x-displayName": "Storage Transactions",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "analytics-overview",
      "x-displayName": "Overview",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  The Analytics API endpoints enable integrations with 3rd party applications to allow pushing test results to and retrieving test results from FarmENGAGE.\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "Soil Tests",
      "x-displayName": "Soil Tests",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "Tissue Tests",
      "x-displayName": "Tissue Tests",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "Scouting Reports",
      "x-displayName": "Scouting Reports",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  The Scouting Report endpoints enable partners to access the scouting report content via API. The GET Scouting Report endpoint returns a list of all the scouting reports in the Organization along with their respective Scouting Report IDs. The Scouting Report IDs can then be used to access the Scouting Report details as well as linked images.\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "documents-overview",
      "x-displayName": "Overview",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  The Documents API enables users to upload and access documents. These documents may be associated with Materials, Bin Transactions, or Scouting photos.\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "Documents",
      "x-displayName": "Documents",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "Imagery-overview",
      "x-displayName": "Overview",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  The Imagery API endpoints enable the upload of GeoTIFF images. In FarmENGAGE, these images will be processed and clipped to any Crop Zones that have boundaries that overlap the imagery area and data ranges that include the imagery acquisition date. When working with an Advisor, Imagery Templates can be assigned for imagery colorization in FarmENGAGE.\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "Images",
      "x-displayName": "Images",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "Image Templates",
      "x-displayName": "Image Templates",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "units-overview",
      "x-displayName": "Overview",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  The Units APIs provide detailed information about the units that are returned with different calls.\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "Units",
      "x-displayName": "Units",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  The Units APIs return Units for different data types such as Materials, Contracts, or Layer Sensors.\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "adapt-introduction",
      "x-displayName": "Overview",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  ADAPT – the Agricultural Data Application Programming Toolkit – is a framework for converting<br />agronomic data between various formats. This toolkit is the result of a collaborative industry effort and includes multiple pieces, including both an open source core framework and a set of plugins. The core framework consists of a common data model, a plugin manager, and a set of utilities for managing units of measure and data representations. The plugins are assemblies which convert data between that common data model and various other data formats.<br />\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "AdaptToken",
      "x-displayName": "AdaptToken",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n</div><figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\">\n\n[<img src=\"/images/adapt_token.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-2513\" />][1]</figure>\n\n [1]: /images/adapt_token_large.png"
    },
    {
      "name": "The ADAPT Data Model",
      "x-displayName": "The ADAPT Data Model",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  The entire functionality of ADAPT is centered on converting data to and from a common Application<br />Data Model. As an application developer, this means you only need to integrate with one data model.<br />The Application Data Model is contained in the AgGateway.ADAPT.ApplicationDataModel.dll assembly.<br />\n</div>\n\n<p class=\"has-normal-font-size\">\n  <strong>Plugin Manager</strong>\n</p>\n\nThe plugin manager is the main entry point when using ADAPT as an SDK. It detects and identifies available plugins, determines which plugin is appropriate for reading a given data source, and marshals plugins and their dependencies as needed. It is contained in the AgGateway.ADAPT.PluginManager.dll assembly.\n\n<p class=\"has-normal-font-size\">\n  <strong>Representation</strong>\n</p>\n\nThe representation assembly, AgGateway.ADAPT.Representation.dll, includes utility classes to help work with units of measure and data representations (similar in concept to ISO DDI’s).\n\n<p class=\"has-normal-font-size\">\n  <strong>Plugins</strong>\n</p>\n\nEach plugin is responsible for translating data between the Application Data Model and a specific external data format. The PTx Trimble plugin supports both the AgGPS and AgData file formats."
    },
    {
      "name": "Getting Started",
      "x-displayName": "Getting Started",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n</div>\n\n<p class=\"has-normal-font-size\">\n  <strong>Referencing ADAPT</strong>\n</p>\n\nYou can reference ADAPT using NuGet by referencing the package at <https://www.nuget.org/packages/AgGatewayADAPTFramework/>&nbsp; If you would rather not use a NuGet client, you can download any version of the package from nuget.org and extract it using a zip utility. In addition to executables, the ADAPT package contains a “Resources” folder that contains RepresentationSystem.xml and UnitSystem.xml. This entire Resources folder needs to be copied to your application’s \\bin directory for the representation system to work.\n\n<p class=\"has-normal-font-size\">\n  <strong>Application Data Model</strong>\n</p>\n\nThe ADAPT Application Data Model is being documented by the AgGateway committee responsible forthe ADAPT project. The project homepage is found at <http://www.adaptframework.org/>\n\n<p class=\"has-normal-font-size\">\n  <strong>Plugin Manager</strong>\n</p>\n\nThe Plugin Manager is used to retrieve and marshal plugins. The PluginFactory must be passed a filesystem directory where the plugin assemblies are stored. Note that while there may be subdirectories (i.e., a folder for each manufacturers’ plugins), the plugin manager will only recurse one level of subdirectories. In other words, passing “C:\\AdaptPlugins\\” to the PluginFactory would cause it to discover plugins inside both “C:\\AdaptPlugins\\” and first level subdirectories like “C:\\AdaptPlugins\\Trimble\\”, but not in “C:\\AdaptPlugins\\Trimble\\AgGPS\\”. Following is sample code which shows how to load plugins and import a datacard.\n\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>PluginFactory factory = new PluginFactory(\"directory containing plugins\");\nList&lt;string&gt; pluginNames = factory.AvailablePlugins;\nforeach(string pluginName in pluginNames)\n{\n  IPlugin plugin = factory.GetPlugin(pluginName);\n  if(plugin.IsDataCardSupported(\"datacard path\")\n  {\n    ApplicationDataModel dataModel = plugin.Import(\"datacard path\");\n    return dataModel;\n  }\n}</code></pre>\n\n<p class=\"has-normal-font-size\">\n  <strong>Representation</strong>\n</p>\n\nThe Representation namespace includes two sets of helper API’s the Unit of Measure System and the Representation System. Together, they form something similar to the ISO DDI system of describing data. A Representation describes the type of data – such as harvest moisture, implement section state, or the GPS receiver offsets. A Unit of Measure provides both the syntax for specifying a unit and the ability to convert between different units of measure or perform arithmetic operations. You can explore the Representations and the units of measure in the included RepresentationSystem.xml and UnitSystem.xml files. Note that these xml files are used by the Representation namespace; if you reference the ADAPT Representation assembly, you will need to include those xml files as resources which are copied to your application’s executing directory.\n\n<p class=\"has-normal-font-size\">\n  <strong>Unit of Measure System</strong>\n</p>\n\nThe simplest way to retrieve unit of measure objects is using static methods on the UnitSystemManager class. To retrieve a UnitOfMeasure instance, pass a unit code to UnitSystemManager.GetUnitOfMeasure(“unit code”). You may also use UN Rec20 unit codes, via UnitSystemManager.FromUNRec20Code(“UN unit code”).\n\nTo help use the units of measure: Once you create a NumericValue, which consists of a value and unit, we offer helper methods for arithmetic operations or unit conversions. If you add the namespace: using AgGateway.ADAPT.Representation.UnitSystem.ExtensionMethods; You will then have access to NumericalValue.Add(double value), NumericalValue.ConvertToUnit(UnitOfMeasure unit), and other helper methods."
    },
    {
      "name": "PTx Trimble ADAPT Plugins",
      "x-displayName": "PTx Trimble ADAPT Plugins",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n</div>\n\nThe ADAPT plugins to read PTx Trimble display data are\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-normal-font-size\">\n  <strong>Initialization</strong>\n</p>\n\nPTx Trimble plugins require a license token to be validated in the initialization process that is acquired through the FarmENGAGE API system. Applications will need to be registered in the FarmENGAGE system to access this API.\n\nTo simplify the process of authenticating and requesting the token, functions have been added to the PTx Trimble plugins that will perform the API calls for a 3rd party application to request a new token. The function is:\n\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>AdaptTokenClient.GetTokenAsync( {AppName}, {AppClientID}, {AppSecret} )\n</code></pre>\n\n\n\nThe token structure returned will have the following:\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-normal-font-size\">\n  <strong>Datacard Paths</strong>\n</p>\n\nThe PTx Trimble plugin will support multiple datacard paths. It will support a path that includes the **AgGPS** or **AgData** directory (ex: C:\\TrimbleData\\AgGPS). It will also support passing the parent directory as well (ex: C:\\TrimbleData).\n\nPlease note that the plugin will not support both file formats at once. If you have a datacard path that has both an AgGPS and AgData directory, it will only read the AgGPS information."
    },
    {
      "name": "telematics-overview",
      "x-displayName": "Overview",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  The Ag Telematics API enables access to detailed data regarding work execution, including:\n</div>\n\n\n\nBy connecting to this API 3rd party applications that address operations and logistics can execute real-time management and detailed post-operation analysis to understand and improve equipment and operator productivity."
    },
    {
      "name": "telematics-concepts",
      "x-displayName": "Concepts",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  The Ag Telematics API is an extension of the Ag Data API (<a href=\"/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">link</a>).  Ag Telematics API users will need to use the Ag Data API to GET FarmENGAGE user Organizations. Additionally, the Ag Data API endpoints can provide additional information that Telematics API users require (for example, Device or Vehicle details).\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "telematics-dependencies",
      "x-displayName": "Dependencies",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  The Ag Telematics API is dependent on and requires applications are also subscribed to the Ag Data API (<a href=\"/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">link</a>). Consequently, Ag Telematics API users need to read the Introduction to the Data API (<a href=\"/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">link</a>) to understand how to exchange data in the FarmENGAGE ecosystem.\n</div>\n\nPTx Trimble Display telematics data availability requires:"
    },
    {
      "name": "telematics-documentation",
      "x-displayName": "Documentation",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  Users can access the Ag Telematics API documentation at this <a href=\"https://telematics-api.trimbleag.com/api-docs/index.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">link</a>\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "telematics-api-access",
      "x-displayName": "API Access",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  For access to the Ag Telematics API please reach out to <a href=\"mailto:api@ptxag.com\">api@ptxag.com</a>.\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "name": "Error Handling",
      "x-displayName": "Error Handling",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  Operations that result in an error due to a problem on the client's part (for example, invalid input) returns standard 4xx codes.<br />5xx codes will be returned if the server encountered an unexpected condition that prevented it from fulfilling the request.\n</div><figure class=\"wp-block-table is-style-stripes\">\n\n<table><tr>\n  <td>\n    <strong>HTTP Response Code</strong>\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    <strong>Error Condition</strong>\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    <strong>Response Body</strong>\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td>\n    400 Bad Request\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    The submitted data was invalid in some way.\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    The error entity, in JSON or XML, is displayed with an applicable specific application error code and message, and possibly detail where available. Each API operation will document the possible application error codes.\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td>\n    401 Unauthorized\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    The user/client API keys were not specified, or were not valid\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    The error code is displayed with a message and a short description.\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td>\n    403 Forbidden\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    Requested operation is invalid.\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    The error code is displayed with a message and short description.\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td>\n    404 Not Found\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    Requested item does not exist.\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    The error code is displayed with a message and short description.\n  </td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n  <td>\n    500 Internal Server Error\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n    Server encountered an unexpected condition.\n  </td>\n  \n  <td>\n  </td>\n</tr></table></figure>"
    },
    {
      "name": "Bookmarks",
      "x-displayName": "Bookmarks",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  The maximum number of records returned for most calls is 1000. In cases where the potential number of records in a response exceeds the maximum number of records that can be returned, a bookmark attribute is included in the response. The token associated with that bookmark then can be passed as a query parameter in a subsequent call to obtain the next set of records. For example, if the total number of records associated with some request is 1,500, the first response will include 1,000 records and a bookmark attribute. A following call including the token from that bookmark would return the remaining 500 records.<br /><!---<br />An example of the bookmark attribute as part of a response is shown below.<br /><br /><img width=\"722\" height=\"93\" src=\"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/mogue_-8AvRE88K1FJxBKEPveylNbPIIDZ-blwjFkIW0USjrrBNrHwig6hGo8W64XYFggdsareAJZG5lx0WsiOHyE2UVRigLN4sY62S-exR85CwNqAqyemhp2SUbnruMH7ggGwT6x6i92u6j9g\" />\n</div>\n-->\n&nbsp;"
    },
    {
      "name": "Links",
      "x-displayName": "Links",
      "description": "<div class=\"overview\">\n  Links are FarmENGAGE’s implementation of <a href=\"https://restfulapi.net/hateoas/\">HATEOAS</a>. These links are useful in discovering additional actions and endpoints that are associated with a particular call. If you do not wish to include links in the response, these can be disabled by using the query parameter includeLinks=false in the request.<br /><br />The following is an example of links being returned for the Clients GET endpoint:\n</div>\n\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>\"links\": &#91;\n               {\n                   \"href\": \"https://api.farmengage.com/prod/externalApi/rogue/3.0/resources/e540056a-8f68-4c4f-ba96-8d88e9ecaea8/clients/ebb17f5c-5b06-4e89-8174-125c4fc463f9\",\n                   \"rel\": \"GetClient\",\n                   \"method\": \"GET\"\n               },\n               {\n                   \"href\": \"https://api.farmengage.com/prod/externalApi/rogue/3.0/resources/e540056a-8f68-4c4f-ba96-8d88e9ecaea8/clients\",\n                   \"rel\": \"CreateClient\",\n                   \"method\": \"POST\"\n               },\n               {\n                   \"href\": \"https://api.farmengage.com/prod/externalApi/rogue/3.0/resources/e540056a-8f68-4c4f-ba96-8d88e9ecaea8/clients/ebb17f5c-5b06-4e89-8174-125c4fc463f9\",\n                   \"rel\": \"UpdateClient\",\n                   \"method\": \"PUT\"\n               },\n               {\n                   \"href\": \"https://api.farmengage.com/prod/externalApi/rogue/3.0/resources/e540056a-8f68-4c4f-ba96-8d88e9ecaea8/clients/ebb17f5c-5b06-4e89-8174-125c4fc463f9/retire\",\n                   \"rel\": \"RetireClient\",\n                   \"method\": \"PATCH\"\n               },\n               {\n                   \"href\": \"https://api.farmengage.com/prod/externalApi/rogue/3.0/resources/e540056a-8f68-4c4f-ba96-8d88e9ecaea8/clients/ebb17f5c-5b06-4e89-8174-125c4fc463f9/unretire\",\n                   \"rel\": \"UnretireClient\",\n                   \"method\": \"PATCH\"\n               },\n               {\n                   \"href\": \"https://api.farmengage.com/prod/externalApi/rogue/3.0/resources/e540056a-8f68-4c4f-ba96-8d88e9ecaea8/farms\",\n                   \"rel\": \"GetFarms\",\n                   \"method\": \"GET\"\n               }\n           ]\n</code></pre>"
    }
  ],
